list git commands what it does

Here’s a clear list of the most commonly used Git commands and what they do 👇

🔹 Basic Git Commands
1️⃣ git init

Creates a new Git repository in your folder.

git init
2️⃣ git clone

Copies an existing repository from a remote source (like GitHub).

git clone <repo-url>
3️⃣ git status

Shows:

Modified files

Staged files

Current branch

git status
4️⃣ git add

Stages files for commit.

git add filename        # Add specific file
git add .               # Add all changes in current folder
git add -A              # Add ALL changes (including deletions)
5️⃣ git commit

Saves staged changes with a message.

git commit -m "Your message"
6️⃣ git push

Uploads your commits to a remote repository.

git push
7️⃣ git pull

Downloads changes from remote and merges them into your branch.

git pull
8️⃣ git fetch

Downloads changes from remote without merging.

git fetch
🔹 Branching Commands
9️⃣ git branch

Shows or creates branches.

git branch            # List branches
git branch new-branch # Create new branch
🔟 git checkout

Switches branches.

git checkout branch-name

Modern alternative:

git switch branch-name
1️⃣1️⃣ git merge

Merges another branch into your current branch.

git merge branch-name
🔹 Undo & Fix Commands
1️⃣2️⃣ git restore

Discard changes in a file.

git restore filename
1️⃣3️⃣ git reset

Unstage files or move commits back.

git reset filename        # Unstage file
git reset --hard HEAD     # Reset everything (dangerous)
1️⃣4️⃣ git revert

Creates a new commit that undoes a previous commit.

git revert commit-id
🔹 History & Info
1️⃣5️⃣ git log

Shows commit history.

git log

Short version:

git log --oneline
1️⃣6️⃣ git diff

Shows changes between versions.

git diff
🔹 Remote Repository Commands
1️⃣7️⃣ git remote -v

Shows connected remote repositories.

git remote -v
1️⃣8️⃣ git remote add

Connects your project to a remote repository.

git remote add origin <repo-url>
🔹 Stashing (Temporary Save)
1️⃣9️⃣ git stash

Temporarily saves changes without committing.

git stash

Restore them:

git stash pop
🎯 Most Important Commands (Daily Use)

If you're just starting, focus on:

git status
git add
git commit -m "message"
git push
git pull
git branch
git checkout